text: Appl Microbiol Biotechnol (2008) 80:15–19 DOI 10.1007/s00253-008-1515-1 Aranciamycin analogs generated by combinatorial biosynthesis show improved antitumor activity Andriy Luzhetskyy & Jens Hoffmann & Stefan Pelzer & Sven-Eric Wohlert & Andreas Vente & Andreas Bechthold Received: 25 March 2008 / Revised: 21 April 2008 / Accepted: 21 April 2008 / Published online: 13 June 2008 # Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg 2008 Abstract Expression of the aranciamycin biosynthetic gene cluster in Streptomyces diastatochromogenes Tü6028 resulted in production of four novel compounds, aranciamy- cins E, F, G, and H with different decorations in the tetra- cyclic backbone. Two derivatives contain a D-amicetose moiety at C7 (aranciamycins F and G), two are hydroxylated at position C1 (aranciamycins E and G), and one is hydroxylated at C13 (aranciamycin F). Analysis of the biological activities of the aranciamycins against two human lines—MCF-7 and MATU—shows surprising tumor cell impact of the hydroxyl group at position C1 on activity. As aranciamycins E and G were the most active derivatives, hydroxylation of the C1 appears to coincide with increased antitumor activity of aranciamycins. Keywords Aranciamycin . Anthracyclines . Combinatorial biosynthesis . Anticancer activity

Hoffmann Schering AG, 13342 Berlin, Germany BIOTECHNOLOGICAL PRODUCTS AND PROCESS ENGINEERING Anthracyclines rank among the most effective antitumor drugs. Doxorubicin and daunorubicin are approved for the treatment of breast and small lung cancer, acute myeloid leukemia, different sarcomas, and others (Arcamone and Cassinelli 1998; Arcamone et al. 1997). However, dose- related side effects are observed during the treatment of patients with different anthracycline drugs. Although novel anthracycline derivatives have been generated during the last 20 years (Arcamone et al. 1997; Gianni et al. 2003; Kratz et al. 2006) it is still of importance to develop novel derivatives with less toxicity and improved effectivity. The chemical structure of anthracyclines makes their chemical synthesis difficult. Combinatorial biosynthesis appears to be a promising tool for the generation of novel anthracycline derivatives. One example for the successful application of combinatorial biosynthesis for the generation of a derivative is the generation of epirubicin, a compound with decreased cardiotoxicity (Madduri et al. 1998). This compound was obtained after genetic modification of the biosynthetic pathways for daunorubicin and doxorubicin (Luzhetskyy and Bechthold 2005).

Aranciamycins, which belong to the anthracycline group of natural products, have been isolated from Streptomyces echinatus (Keller-Schierlein and Müller 1970). Aranciamy- cin A, the main compound, shows weak antitumor activity and is closely related to steffimycin B (Bols et al. 1992; Broasky and Reusser 1974). In addition, aranciamycin A appears to be specific inhibitors of Clostridium histolyticum collagenase (Bols et al. 1992). Aranciamycin A consists of the aglycone aranciamycinone and the sugar 2-O-methyl-L- rhamnose. It differs from the very well known anthracy- clines (e.g. daunomycin, adriamycin, carminomycin) with respect to the substitution of ring A and the sugar moiety, which does not carry an amino group. Recently we have reported the cloning and sequencing of the aranciamycin biosynthetic gene cluster from S. echinatus (Luzhetskyy et al. 2007). We have shown an impact of deoxysugar moiety on the antitumor activity of aranciamycins. Here we describe the generation of additional four novel derivatives after expression of the aranciamycin gene cluster in S. diastatochromogenes Tü6028. Antitumor activities of new and described compounds are compared and structure- activity relationships of aranciamycins are discussed. Appl Microbiol Biotechnol (2008) 80:15–19

The successful expression of cosmid 41–2C-06 in different strains and the generation of several novel aranciamycins have been described (Luzhetskyy et al. 2007). In this manuscript we are describing the structure of four addi- tional compounds which were detected in the extract of S. diastatochromogenes Tü6028 containing cosmid 41–2C- 06. These new aranciamycins were named aranciamycins E, F, G and H (Fig. 1). All four new aranciamycins do not contain the methoxy group at position C8 in comparison to aranciamycin A. Aranciamycins E and G both contain hydroxyl group in the C1 position, in addition, aranciamycin G contains a D-amicetose attached at the C7-OH position. Aranciamycin F contains a hydroxyl group in the C-13 position and a D-amicetose attached at the C7-OH position. Finally, aranciamycin H lacks the hydroxyl group at the C7 position in comparison to aranciamycinone (Fig. 1). Due to the small amount of aranciamycin E, it was not possible to observe all signals of a 13C-NMR – spectrum. Therefore, 13C data were assigned through connectivity of the HMQS experiment. These data are in accordance with data of the aranciamycin G aglycon, which is identical to aranciamycin E (see Appendix). Activities against MaTu and MCF7 cell lines of the new aranciamycins E and G, together with the previously described aranciamycins B, C and D and aranciamycinone were determined using the KV-assay (Materials and Methods). Aranciamycinone was not active against MaTu cells and shows very weak (GI50 was > 10 μM) activity against MCF7 cell lines. In contrast, aranciamycins B and D containing the trideoxysugars L-rhodinose and D- amicetose respectively showed activity. Surprisingly aran- cialycin E lacking any deoxysugar at the C7-OH position but containing an OH-group at the C1 position showed the best inhibition activity (Fig. 2). Anthracyclines play an important role in the treatment of many neoplastic diseases. But at the same time they induce cardiomyopathy and other heart failure (Minotti et al. 2004) and there is a need for derivatives with less toxicity. The Fig. 2 Activities of aranciamycins against MCF7 (a) and MaTu (b) cell lines. 1 – aranciamycin D; 2 – aranciamycin B; 3 – aranciamycin C; 4 – aranciamycin G; 5 – aranciamycinone; 6 – aranciamycin E chemical synthesis of anthracyclines is not a trivial operation since they are large and chemically labile molecules. Biosynthetic approach is an alternative way to produce novel analogs of natural products (Floss 2006). There are many successful application of combinatorial biosynthesis for generation of the new anthracyclines (Kantola et al. 2003). Mainly focus is made on the modification of the glycoside components of anthracyclines since this part of the molecules is crucially important for the anticancer activity (Madduri et al. 1998; Olano et al. 2008; Luzhetskyy et al. 2007).

Aranciamycin and steffimycin are very similar com- pounds with very unique structural features not present in other anthracyclines. These include a methoxy group in the C8 position and the neutral deoxysugar L-rhamnose in the C7-O position. In addition steffimycin contains another methoxy group in the C2 position and a keto group in the C10 position. Both gene clusters responsible for the biosynthesis of both compounds have been cloned, se- quenced and expressed to generate novel derivatives (Gullon et al. 2007; Luzhetsky et al. 2007). 1  2  3  4 5 6 Control  0.1%EtOH  1  2  3  4 5 6 Control  0.1%EtOH

Taken all results together 8 novel aranciamycin and 12 novel steffimycin derivatives have been generated by genetic engineering. In both studies the relevance of the sugar moiety for anticancer activity was demonstrated. Aranciamycins B and D containing the trideoxysugars L- rhodinose and D-amicetose, respectively, showed better inhibition activities than aranciamycinone. Salas and coworkers showed that D-digitoxosyl-8-demethoxy- 10-deoxysteffimycin was 50 times more active than D-olivosyl-8-demethoxy-10-deoxysteffimycin. Both com- pounds differ in the configuration of the OH group at the C3′ - position (Olano et al. 2008). But in contrast, the activity of aranciamycin C containing the unusual meth- ylated deoxysugar L-axenose was similar to the activity of the aglycone, thus the structure of the sugar is a very important issue (Bols et al. 1992; Luzhetskyy et al. 2007). The glycosyltransferases responsible for the attachment of variety of different sugars are AraGT and StfG. Sequence comparison of AraGT and StfG revealed that both enzymes share 53% identical amino acids. This is surprisingly low since both glycosyltransferases recognize very similar acceptor substrates (Fig. 1), recognize the same deoxysugar (L-rhamnose), and combine both substrates at the same position of the aglycon. Other glycosyltransferase, LanGT1 and LndGT1 and LanGT4 and LndGT4 (Luzhestkyy et al. 2005; Ostash et al. 2004), which recognize the same sugar

donors and the same acceptor substrate share around 75% identical amino acids. Most of the differences between AraGT and StfG are located in the N-terminal part between amino acids 55 and 110 which form the N3 loop and between amino acids 160 and 200 which form the N5 loop (Fig. 3). These both loops are known to be involved in aglycon recognition and binding (Luzhetskyy et al. 2008). Small differences between both acceptor substrates (Fig. 1) may be responsible for the differences in the amino acid composition of both loops. The flexibility of both enzymes towards the acceptor substrate also indicates that nature developed different solutions to allow both enzymes glycosylation. In contrast the C- terminal parts of AraGT and StfG are more conserved (80% identical amino acids). The region within Cβ5 and Cα5, supposed to be involved in binding of hexose moieties, is usually poorly conserved within antibiotic glycosyltrans- ferases. As this region is different in other glycosyltrans- ferases recognizing dTDP-L-rhamnose (e.g. ElmGT and SpnG) the donor sugar can not be responsible for the striking similarity of AraGT and StfG. Beside the sugar, hydroxylation patterns are very important for activity. One of the most active compounds is aranciamycin E which contains a hydroxyl group at C1 but no sugar at C7. Interestingly, an OH-group at the C1 position is present in the very active compounds ciner- Appl Microbiol Biotechnol (2008) 80:15–19 Appl Microbiol Biotechnol (2008) 80:15–19

ubins, isorhodomycins and nogalamycin (David et al. 1980; Beinker et al. 2006). As the C1 position is not hydroxylated in anthracyclines which are in clinical use hybrid-anthracyclines generated by modification at this position could have novel interesting toxicological profiles. Our data and the data published by the group of Prof. Salas, Oviedo, Spain, clearly indicate that genetic engineering is a powerful and fast method to generate novel glycosylated and hydroxylated anthracyclines.
